  "prompt_text": "Design a rate limiter for an API. What data structures and algorithms would you use?",
  "response_text": "To design a rate limiter for an API, I would use a combination of data structures and algorithms to efficiently manage and control the number of requests from a single user or IP address. Here's a high-level approach:\n\n1. **Data Structures:**\n   - Hash Map (or Dictionary in Python): To store IP addresses or user IDs as keys and the number of requests made within a specific time window as values.\n   - Priority Queue (or Heap in Python): To maintain the order of requests based on their timestamps, allowing us to easily handle requests within the time window.\n\n2. **Algorithms:**\n   - Leaky Bucket: This algorithm is commonly used for rate limiting. It maintains a bucket of a certain size and allows a certain number of requests per time unit. If the bucket is full, additional requests are discarded. The bucket \"leaks\" at a constant rate, allowing more requests to be accepted over time.\n   - Sliding Window: This algorithm maintains a window of a specific size (e.g., 60 seconds) and counts the number of requests within that window. If the count exceeds the maximum allowed requests within the window, additional requests are discarded.\n\n3. **Implementation:**\n   - Initialize an empty hash map and a priority queue.\n   - On each incoming request, check the IP address or user ID in the hash map. If it exists, increment the count in the hash map and update the timestamp in the priority queue. If it doesn't exist, add it to the hash map and priority queue with a count of 1 and the current timestamp.\n   - Check the size of the priority queue and the count in the hash map for the current IP address or user ID. If the size of the priority queue exceeds the bucket size or the count exceeds the maximum allowed requests within the sliding window, discard the oldest request in the priority queue and decrement the count in the hash map.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 9\nG (Goal Directedness): 10\nP (Pattern Recognition): 10\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 9\nQ (Query Interpretation): 10\nC (Contextual Awareness): 9\nY (Affective Modeling): 7\nF (Flexibility): 8\nD (Depth of Processing): 9\n---END RATINGS---",
